## Setup

- Harness: [gemma4-audio](https://github.com/twangodev/gemma4-audio), `jiwer` for WER/CER/MER/WIL.
- Backend: **vLLM**, bf16. `batch_size=16` in the config, but the audio path is currently broken for batching, so everything runs one sample at a time. RTFx numbers are a floor.
- Hardware: **RTX 6000 Pro Blackwell, 96 GB**.
- Prompt:

```
Transcribe the following speech segment in its original language.
* Only output the transcription, with no newlines.
* When transcribing numbers, write the digits, i.e. write 1.7
  and not one point seven, and write 3 instead of three.
```

## WER across the suite

<WerHeatmap />

E4B stays within 2–3 WER points of the leaders on clean read speech. The gap widens on noisy spontaneous audio. On LS Clean specifically, **E4B (4.17%) beats Whisper base.en (4.25%)**. A 4B generalist holding its own against a 74M CTC model isn't bad.

E2B on AMI: 202% WER. The model wrote about twice as many words as the reference. E4B lands at 41%. Still bad, but at least legible.

## Speed vs accuracy

<WerRtfxScatter />

Competitor RTFx is batched. Ours is single-stream. Apples to oranges. Once vLLM batching lands, the Gemma dots shift right. Probably not all the way to Parakeet's 3,386×.

## Error composition

<ErrorCompositionChart />

Insertions climb on noisy data. LS Clean: 0.49% insertion rate. AMI: 20% (E4B), **180% (E2B)**. That's the LM prior making things up when the audio is hard to decode.

CER/WER tells the same story from another angle. Clean ASR runs around 0.43 on clean data, and E2B matches that on LS Clean. On AMI, E2B's ratio jumps to **1.14**. CER exceeds WER because each hallucinated insertion is a long run of characters. The failure mode is generation, not misrecognition.

## Where Gemma 4 actually breaks

<DurationHallucinationChart />

Bucket every sample by audio duration and you get a U-shape. Anything over 3s is fine. Under that it falls apart. Sub-1s is a cliff.

- **Sub-1s, E2B**: 2,203% mean WER, 1,766% insertion rate, **8.7% are literal refusals** ("I'm sorry, I cannot…").
- **Sub-1s, E4B**: 220% / 164% / 0.9%. Better by an order of magnitude. Still broken.

When the audio is too short to constrain the token distribution, the instruction-tuned prior takes over. More parameters help. Neither variant is speech-first.

AMI-wide refusal rate for E2B: **3.98%** (503 samples). A five-line regex would catch almost all of them.

### The worst single sample

1.3-second LibriSpeech clip. Reference: `a story`. E2B produced:

> I'm sorry, but you haven't provided any audio or text for me to transcribe. Please provide the audio or text you would like me to transcribe.

WER of 14.0. 26 insertions. A CTC model physically can't do this; *I'm sorry* isn't in its vocabulary. E4B got the same clip right.

